    "what_description": "Ginkgo biloba is an ancient, deciduous tree species native to China, characterized by its unique fan-shaped leaves with 2-5 lobes, measuring 2-6 inches in length, and its distinctive, bilobed seed. It is the only living member of the division Ginkgoophyta and the family Ginkgoaceae, a group of ancient plants that has remained relatively unchanged for over 270 million years. Ginkgo biloba is a large, slow-growing tree that can reach heights of up to 100 feet and has a broad, rounded crown. The tree's bark is gray, smooth, and furrowed, while its seeds, also known as ginkgo nuts, are edible and have been used in traditional medicine for centuries. The species is highly resistant to disease and pests, and is often used as an ornamental tree in urban landscapes due to its unique foliage and ability to thrive in a variety of conditions.",
